  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 대춘(大椿) : '
    value: 상고(上古)에 대춘이 있었는데, 8천 년을 봄으로 삼고 8천 년을 가을로 삼았다 하였다. 《莊子》
  - key: '[주-D002] 꿈에 내가 …… 위로 갔네 : '
    value: 장주(莊周)가 꿈에 나비가 되어, 훨훨 나는 나비로서 스스로 유쾌하였다는 구절이 있다. 《莊子》
  - key: '[주-D003] 태미(大微) : '
    value: 별 이름인데 천자(天子)의 뜰이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 두 눈이 …… 푸르네 : '
    value: 진(晉)나라 완적(阮籍)이 눈알을 굴려 희게 뜨기도 하고 푸르게 뜨기도 했는데, 뜻에 맞는 사람을 만나면 푸른 눈으로 대하였다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 피어나는 …… 신명(神明)의 힘이라 : '
    value: 이 일절(一節)은 두보(杜甫)가 오래되고 큰 잣나무를 두고 지은 시에서 나온 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 음강씨(陰康氏)와 대정씨(大庭氏) : '
    value: 태고 때의 임금들이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 헌원씨(軒轅氏)의 탁록(涿鹿) : '
    value: 헌원씨(軒轅氏)가 탁록의 들에서 치우(蚩尤)와 크게 싸웠다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 포희씨(包羲氏)의 …… 것이요 : '
    value: 《주역》의 팔괘(八卦)는 상고(上古)에 포희씨(包羲氏)가 처음 그었다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 공공(共工)과 …… 돌이다 : '
    value: 공공씨(共工氏)와 전욱(顓頊)이 다투다가 부주산(不周山)에 부딪치어 천주(天柱)를 꺾으니, 하늘이 서북(西北)으로 기울어지므로 여와씨(女媧氏)가 돌을 다듬어서 하늘을 기웠다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 후예(后羿)가 …… 쏨이며 : '
    value: 요(堯) 임금 때에 해 열 개가 한꺼번에 뜨니 초목이 모두 마르므로, 후예(后羿)가 활로 쏘아 아홉 해를 떨어뜨렸다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 구하(九河)가 결궤(決潰)됨이요 : '
    value: 우(禹)가 홍수(洪水)를 다스릴 때에 결궤(決潰)된 아홉 하수를 치수(治水)하였다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 인(因)하여 옳고[因是] : '
    value: 각기 저는 옳고 남은 그르다 하기 때문에 ‘이것으로 인하여 저것이 있고 저것으로 인하여 이것이 있어’ 인하여 옳은 것도 있고 인하여 그른 것도 있다 하였다. 《莊子》
  - key: '[주-D013] 물론(物論)을 …… 보네 : '
    value: 세상에 서로 옳으니 그르니 하는 물론(物論)을 다 같이 가지런하게 본다는 뜻. 《莊子 齊物論》
  - key: '[주-D014] 팽조(彭祖) : '
    value: 팽조(彭祖)는 8백 년이나 오래 살았다는 사람이었다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 칠원(漆園) : '
    value: 장자가 칠원(漆園) 땅에 관리 노릇을 한 적이 있으므로 그를 칠원이라고도 부른다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 반우(反隅)할 : '
    value: 공자의 말에, “한 귀퉁이를 들어 말하는 것은 듣건대, 세 귀퉁이로써 돌이켜 생각해 알아야 한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D017] 견백(堅白) : '
    value: 전국 시대(戰國時代)에 공손룡(公孫龍)이, “돌은 하나인 것 같으나 단단한 돌의 성질과 흰돌의 빛깔은 각각 다른 돌이다. 그것은 촉각(觸覺)에서 아는 돌과 시각(視覺)으로 보는 돌이 따로 있다.”는 독특한 논리(論理)를 고집하였다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 변풍(變風)도 …… 끝이나니 : '
    value: 《시경》에 정풍(正風)과 변풍(變風)의 구별이 있는데, 변풍은 음란하고 원망하는 시가 많다. 그러나 그것도 뜻이 마침내는 예의(禮義)에 벗어나지 않은 것이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 육기(六氣) : '
    value: 음(陰)ㆍ양(陽)ㆍ풍(風)ㆍ우(雨)ㆍ회(晦)ㆍ삭(朔)이다.
  - key: '[주-D020] 삼황(三皇)은 …… 세워[立極] : '
    value: 하늘을 이어받아[繼天] 인도(人道)의 표준[極]을 세운다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D021] 방훈(放勳)은 …… 큰 지혜로다. : '
    value: 방훈(放勳 요(堯)의 별칭)의 덕을 칭찬하면서, “안안(安安)하다.” 하였고, 맹자(孟子)는, “순(舜)은 큰 지혜[大智]이다.” 하였다. 《書經》
  - key: '[주-D022] 사악(四岳)과 …… 보좌함이요 : '
    value: 사악(四岳)은 요(堯)의 신하로서 사방(四方)의 방백(方伯)들이요, 구관(九官)은 순(舜)의 신하로 우(禹)ㆍ고요(皐陶)ㆍ후직(后稷) 등 아홉 사람이다.
  - key: '[주-D023] 백익(伯益)과 아형(阿衡) : '
    value: 백익(伯益)은 우(禹)의 가장 어진 신하요, 아형(阿衡)은 탕(湯)의 가장 어진 신하인 이윤(伊尹)의 별칭이다.
  - key: '[주-D024] 자포(自暴)하고 자기(自棄) : '
    value: 맹자는, “예의(禮義)가 아닌 말만을 하는 것을 자포(自暴)라 하고, 내 몸이 인의(仁義)를 행할 수 없다고 하는 것을 자기(自棄)라 한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D025] 가장 …… 쌓은 것 : '
    value: 숙손목자(叔孫穆子)의 말에, “가장 상등은 덕을 세우는 것이요, 다음은 공(功)을 세우는 것이며, 다음은 말을 세우는 것[立言]이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D026] 이 춘(椿)은 …… 소요(逍遙)함이랴 : '
    value: 장자의 첫 편이 〈소요유(逍遙遊)〉편인데, 모든 구속을 초월하여 〈정신적으로〉 소요하게 노닌다는 뜻이다. 대춘(大椿)은 그 편에서 나온 문구(文句)이다.
  - key: '[주-D027] 사문(斯文) : '
    value: 공자의 말에서 나온 문구인데, 문왕(文王)이 죽은 뒤에 자신이 이어받은 이 도(道)라는 뜻이다. 후세의 선비들은 유학(儒學)을 사문(斯文)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D028] 방외(方外) : '
    value: 예의 법도의 밖이란 말인데 예의 법도를 초월하였다는 뜻이다. 여기서는 장자를 가리킨 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 面 : '
    value: 而
english:
  title: The Great Parasol Tree
  author: Nam Hyo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In dream I rode upon a butterfly,
    Fluttering upward through the sky,
    Where frozen rain dampens the dust,
    And whirlwinds clear the path.

    Past the silver river, beyond the stellar mansions,
    Through the celestial court I journeyed,
    Where I met the Great Sage in the nine heights—
    His eyes gazed upon me, and turned blue.

    I bowed in reverence, received him with honor,
    And stepping forward, began to speak:
    "I was born on this earthly plane,
    Near thirty springs have passed.
    In solitude and leisure I have dwelled,
    My knowledge narrow, my learning scant.
    Beyond the world's veil, by fortune's grace,
    I have met one of strange wisdom.
    Will you teach me extraordinary words,
    To moisten this fish parched from drought?"

    The Great Sage, hearing my plea, took pity,
    And offered words most precious and rare:
    "My words are vast and without foundation,
    Like the Milky Way stretching without end.

    In the dim antiquity of old,
    There existed a Great Parasol Tree,
    Growing in boundless, desolate plains.
    Its bark, frost-bitten, smoothed by rain,
    Its trunk of iron, weathered and stripped.
    Ants tunnel through roots a hundred arm-spans wide,
    Phoenixes nest in leaves ten thousand lengths high.

    The Rain Master hangs his cosmic gourd,
    The Thunder God conceals his lightning bolts.
    The flourishing of its bloom shows heaven's work,
    The support it receives shows divine power.

    It takes sixteen thousand years as a spring and autumn,
    Eight hundred and forty-two months as a morning and evening.
    Vast and vast is all beneath heaven—
    Human generations rise and fall,
    Yet the Parasol stands alone,
    Witnessing countless ages pass.

    What appear as flies turning the millstone
    Are the reigns of Yin Kang and Tai Ting exchanging rule.
    Mosquitoes humming like thunder
    Are Hsüan-yüan's battle at Cho-lu.
    What seems like children at play
    Is Fu-hsi drawing his eight trigrams.
    What passes like a clod of earth
    Is Kung Kung striking Not-zhou.
    What appears as a pellet
    Is Nü-wa mending heaven with stone.
    What seems like thistle-down arrows
    Is Hou-yi shooting down the suns.

    A cup of water spilled on the hall
    Is the nine rivers breaking their bounds,
    Half a stone crumbling
    Is the Pillar of Earth toppling.

    In one blink, one breath—
    Five hundred years of the Xia dynasty pass.
    As swift as morning to evening—
    Six hundred years of the Shang.
    When the Way of Wen and Wu was lost,
    Zhou moved eastward.
    When Qi and Jin vied for hegemony,
    The Spring and Autumn era came forth.

    Observing heaven and earth's transformations,
    Neighboring the infinite and eternal,
    Unwithered by frost and wind,
    Enduring as spring through ten thousand ages.

    The cicada lives spring to summer's death,
    The morning mushroom sprouts at evening, fades by dawn.
    They know not autumn and spring, new moon and full—
    How could they comprehend the Parasol's long years?

    This is the distinction between great and small,
    What even the Yellow Emperor pondered with doubt,
    What common folk deride and mock."

    I heard and questioned him further:
    "Your words are grand, astounding all who listen,
    Yet my humble view differs.
    Will you hear me out?

    When heaven and earth first divided,
    Odd and even came into being,
    Categories received their varied influences,
    And ten thousand things were born.

    That things differ is their very nature—
    Some small, some large,
    Some short, some long,
    Some numerous, some rare,
    Some enduring, some perishing.

    Without loss there is no gain,
    Without weakness there is no strength,
    Without death and life, no glory,
    Without day and night, no light.

    The unity of great and small, gain and loss,
    Is the same principle as day and night, death and life.
    The Way pervades everywhere—
    Why distinguish between this and that?

    Therefore, the supreme Way accepts all,
    The great vision harmonizes all things.
    Heaven does not boast over earth,
    The sun does not tower over the moon,
    Fliers do not mock the swimmers,
    Motion does not surpass stillness.

    Who points to say this is wrong,
    Who points to say that is right?
    Yao and Jie both return to dust,
    Confucius and Robber Zhi both die.

    Nothing surpasses an autumn hair,
    Yet Mount Tai becomes small.
    None lives longer than a child who dies young,
    Yet Peng-tsu aged quickly.

    The phoenix rises with strokes of its wings,
    The owl clutches carrion and trembles in fear.
    The great Peng transforms and soars ninety thousand li southward,
    The quail finds freedom in common grass.

    Each preserves its nature,
    Their meanings are one.

    When heaven creates things,
    It strengthens them according to their nature.
    Destruction comes not as enemy,
    Nourishment not as favor.
    All are born together following principle,
    All perish together in transformation's flow.

    Does the mushroom's brief year harm it?
    Does the Parasol's long life help it?

    Knowing that smallness can be peace,
    Grandeur can be dismissed.
    Knowing death can be lightened,
    Long life can be refused.

    I thought to hear strange teachings from you,
    Yet you speak only of the Parasol Tree.
    I fear the true intent of creation
    Lies neither here nor there."

    The Great Sage replied: "Ah! You err!
    The virtuous seek understanding through words,
    The wise know ten things by hearing one.

    I began with Zhuangzi's jest in the Lacquer Garden,
    To hint at the mystery of the supreme Way.
    Yet you see only the surface,
    Lacking the knowledge to turn back and understand.
    Instead you cling to the sophistry of Hard-and-White,
    Forcing forth your small, foolish views.

    Even wayward verse ends in propriety and righteousness—
    The Parasol Tree also serves as metaphor for the Way.

    For the ultimate person has no self,
    The spiritual person acts without artifice,
    Forgetting self and losing self,
    There is neither right nor wrong.

    Riding the truth of the six vital forces,
    They know heaven and earth's hidden mechanism,
    Attaining ultimate joy, they play in ultimate joy,
    Calm and thoughtless, utterly free.

    How is this different from the Parasol,
    Transcending dust and uniquely strange?

    The bound harbor worry,
    The stubborn cling to convention—
    Trembling and anxious,
    Verbose and agitated.

    When still, like an oath sworn,
    When moving, like an arrow shot.
    Trying to win, they waste their vital essence,
    Until at last they grow old and weary.

    Why such narrow, small perception?
    Like the morning mushroom knowing not new moon from full.

    Thus the wise and foolish are not equal,
    The great and small have different degrees.
    How can the foolish know the wise,
    How can the small reach the great?

    Mere recognition of honor and shame—
    Song Rong cannot know Liezi's riding wind,
    Only avoiding blame on foot.
    How could Liezi know the ultimate person's actionlessness?

    Consider: the Three Sovereigns inherited heaven,
    The Five Emperors established the pole.
    Majestic and boundless,
    Harmonious and profound.

    Fang-hun ruled with ease,
    Chung-hua possessed great wisdom.
    Yu received the succession from Shun,
    Tang revolutionized the latter Xia.

    With virtue and longevity,
    With name and station.
    The Four Mountains and Nine Ministers supported them,
    Bo-yi and Ah-heng stood at their sides.

    They renewed the people through encouragement,
    Placed all under heaven in benevolence and longevity.
    Their names bright as sun and moon,
    Their virtue matching heaven and earth's endurance.

    Those in darkness know nothing,
    Turning from the plumb line to follow the crooked.
    Abandoning themselves to ruin,
    Becoming the world's great criminals,
    Degrading with grass and wood,
    Their names not passing to later ages.

    Thus Yao's death differs from Robber Zhi's,
    Doing good differs from doing evil.
    Yet you blur them into sameness—
    Greatly foolish and deluded!

    Ah! The highest establishes virtue—
    This is called the Parasol.
    The hopelessly ignorant never change—
    This is called the morning mushroom.

    Therefore this Parasol Tree—
    Is it Zhuangzi's freedom alone?
    Or does it also touch on the Way of Culture itself?"

    Hearing this, I marveled,
    And bowing twice in thanks, replied:
    "Myself am but rash and coarse,
    My learning scattered and confused.
    Asking of teachings beyond convention,
    I have now received the great method of learning.
    Hearing small, I have heard great,
    And heard how the sage differs from the common."

    Stretching and yawning, suddenly I woke—
    Only the moon falling on an empty beam.
